segments.text: You're talking about the core.
Yeah, well, the organization and the discipline and the relationships are all invaluable, I think, to me.
I kind of feel like some potential student asking, are you going to have to get in the Corps?
And the response is, sir, it's a privilege to be in the Corps.
And I really feel somewhat that way about it.
It was an experience that I would certainly not want to have missed.
And I value Rice, certainly.
in a different way.
I never would have had that experience if I'd stayed there.
So that element, the living in the dormitory and the military part, discipline, were all significant.
One of the other great advantages in this pre-decor situation is that
You're welcome.
There's an Aggie anywhere.
And I've traveled.
After I left A&M in 58, I've traveled, well, I shouldn't say all over the world, but a lot of international places and certainly a lot in the United States.
I was with the Asgrove Seed Company.
It wasn't a big company, but we had operations everywhere.
all the way from the east coast to California and Texas to New England.
So you'd run into Aggies everywhere, and it was just a wonderful experience to be able to greet each other and know that you were.
And then the third ring was something for quick recognition and the sincerity of it, too.
It was fun.
Impressed me.
It's not just, oh, there you are in Aggie, et cetera.
There's some meaning in the motion to it.
Let's make believe that someone gives you a check for a million dollars, and there's only one requirement they attach to that check.
You must give it to Texas A&M, but you decide what the money's going to be used for.
If that were to happen, what would you want them to do with that million dollars?
Want A&M to do?
What would you do?
If you had a million dollars you could pass on to anyone, what would be what you'd want them to spend it for?
Well, just an off-the-cuff reaction is to expand the course some way so that more people could have the benefit of that experience.
That may not be exactly the type of thing you have in mind.
And or scholarships for students.
Would it matter what they studied, in your preference?
No, I think I would divert, well, I don't know whether you could do that with a million dollars, but I would think some diversity would be desirable, as far as I'm personally concerned.
I don't want them all in agronomy, for example.
I wouldn't want to give it all to agronomy if I would be doing that.
probably restrict it to agriculture and make it broad enough that it would broaden the potential of it rather than narrow it too much.
Last question.
What feelings do you have when your heart touches anything?
On balance, I certainly have a very
very favorable reaction to my experience with Texas A&M.
I think, since I'm not having to run it, I think there's an institution of higher learning in the state and largely funded by the state that should really look ahead as to what it could be
institution contribute to the future in the education of the youth that are coming up.
And I don't know exactly how to do this, but I think it's imperative that we educate a broader range of our society.
If we don't, we'll decline instead of go up there.
And that may just be my point.
I know we speak of a method term a lot of times, but I'm trying to look at it as an overall situation that we need to educate the youth regardless of the evidence that we're using.
And it's only in doing this that we'll be able to continue to develop and grow, and to me that's a
To me, it ought to be the greatest concern of the administration of the university.
And perhaps, well, you've been in budget situations all your life, so I'm not telling you anything, but there's never enough money to do all the things you want, so you must make choices.
I really think the education we use should have priority over some of these high polluting research situations, as an example.
And I've been in research most of my life.
Sure, there has to be some.
is the attention to the youth and both enabling them to come to school.
And I don't, I have a little trouble with this, you telling me there's half the school or top 10% of the classrooms.
That means there are a lot of other people that aren't getting an opportunity for an education, at least here.
The difficulty with the alternative is how large can you let the enrollment become and to whom do you give preference?
I'm well aware that it's a difficult situation.
I just saw it as a reality.
We do need to be providing education.
Some of it is possible to...
And I'm not one of those people that everybody's got to have a college education.
But to particularly offer the potential to, I haven't.
I still get the Harvard Review of Propaganda, maybe.
But they, I think they follow.
I don't think it's just an episode.
It's a policy of providing an educated course.
They have high academic requirements to get in.
But they won't refuse a student because of financial needs.
They made a commitment to fund the qualified student as far as financial needs are concerned if they've got the interest and abilities and technicalities to go there.
It's not a simple thing, but I think

University, I'll keep that in mind all the time, about doing what it can to educate the youth of this state, and particularly, and this is where, I don't know just how you perceive, some of this may mean education of a less, of less than the elite, if you don't look at it that way, but we need the people in all of
aspects of society.
I think we're going to have to do something to help them out.
Have we left any important topics out?
I'd have a hard time recounting what all was said.
I think all of the significance of what I'm thinking.
